  "prompt": "Thermodynamics: What is the difference between wet steam and dry steam?",
  "response": "The primary difference between wet steam and dry steam lies in their moisture content and phase composition.\n\n1. **Wet Steam**: \n   - Wet steam, also known as saturated steam, contains a mixture of both liquid water and steam (vapor). \n   - It is at the saturation temperature corresponding to its pressure, meaning it is on the edge of phase change between liquid and vapor.\n   - The moisture in wet steam signifies that it is not purely gaseous; instead, it consists of steam droplets suspended within the vapor. \n   - Engineers and technicians often refer to the quality of wet steam, which is the fraction of steam in the mixture; a quality of 1 (or 100%) means all vapor, and a quality of 0 (or 0%) means all liquid.\n\n2. **Dry Steam**: \n   - Dry steam, often referred to as superheated steam, contains no water droplets and is entirely in the steam phase.\n   - It occurs when steam is heated beyond its saturation temperature, removing all liquid water content.\n   - Dry steam is used in applications where moisture can cause problems, such as in turbines, since it ensures that the steam is purely vapor and avoids damage or inefficiency caused by liquid drops.\n   \nIn summary, wet steam is a mixture of water and steam at equilibrium, whereas dry steam is entirely vapor and typically at a higher temperature than the saturation temperature.",
